<title>HUNGARY: Lamfalussy declines comment on German gold plan.</title>
<headline>Lamfalussy declines comment on German gold plan.</headline>
<dateline>BUDAPEST 1997-05-17</dateline>
<text>
<p>Alexandre Lamfalussy, president of the European Monetary Institute, declined on Saturday to comment on Germany's plan to revalue its gold reserves to help it meet European monetary union (EMU) targets.</p>
<p>&quot;I have no comment on any question...about (German Finance Minister Theo) Waigel's proposal,&quot; Lamfalussy told Reuters in Hungary where he was delivering a lecture on monetary union.</p>
<p>Waigel said this week if gold reserves were revalued from current low book prices to near normal market level it could help fill an 18 billion mark ($10.6 billion) tax revenue shortfall. --Michael Roddy, Budapest newsroom ++ 36 1 327 4040</p>
